{"title_page": "Shaqra University", "text_new": "{{short description|Government university in Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Infobox university\n| image           = SHAQRA UNIVERSITY LOGO.png\n| caption         = \n| name            = Shaqra University\n| native_name     = \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0634\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0621\n| latin_name      = \n| motto           = \n| established     = 2009\n| type            = Government\n| calendar        = \n| endowment       = \n| staff           = \n| faculty         = \n| president       = [[Awad Alasmari]]\n| provost         = \n| principal       = \n| rector          = Awad_Alasmari\n| chancellor      = \n| vice_chancellor = \n| dean            = \n| head_label      = \n| head            = \n| students        = 32000\n| undergrad       = \n| postgrad        = \n| doctoral        = \n| city            = [[Shaqra]]\n| state           = [[Riyadh Province|Riyadh]]\n| country         = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| campus          = Multiple sites (spread across approx. 450 KM)\n| free_label      = \n| free            = \n| athletics       = \n| colors          = \n| mascot          = \n| nickname        = \n| affiliations    = \n| footnotes       = \n| website         = {{URL|su.edu.sa}}\n| address         = Main Campus, Al Duwadimi Road, Shaqra\n| telephone       = \n| coor            = \n| logo            = \n}}\n\n'''Shaqra University''' (SU) (Arabic: \u0634\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0621 \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 ) is located in [[Shaqra, Saudi Arabia]] ({{cvt|190|km}} northwest of [[Riyadh]]). It comes under the supervision of the Ministry of Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.4icu.org/reviews/13869.htm|title=Shaqra University {{!}} Ranking & Review|website=www.4icu.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mofa.gov.sa/sites/mofaen/ServicesAndInformation/news/MinistryNews/Pages/ArticleID2011723115950258.aspx|title=Saudi Ambassador to Australia and New Zealand Meets Dean of Shaqra University |agency= Kingdom of Saudi Arabia - Ministry of Foreign Affairs |website= www.mofa.gov.sa |language= en |access-date=2018-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/327384|title=King approves 4 new universities|date=2009-08-25|work=Arab News|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref> The University has twenty-four colleges in various disciplines. It is headquartered in Shaqra with its various colleges being geographically spread in the largest area of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia covering several governorates and sub-governorates lying in the west of Riyadh.\n\n== History ==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2018}}\nShaqra University was established on the 3rd of Ramadan 1430 (Gregorian date 24 August 2009), as per the decision of King Abdullah bin Abdulaziz Al Saud, the Prime Minister and the Chairman of the Higher Education Council, Saudi Arabia.\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+Previous Rectors\n!\n!Name\n|\n|-\n|1\n|Dr. Saeed bin Turki Al-Mulla\n|\n|-\n|2\n|Dr Khalid bin Saad bin Said\n|\n|-\n|3\n|Dr Khalid Bin Saad Al Muqrin\n|\n|-\n|4\n|Dr. Adnan  Alshiha\n|\n|}\n<br />\n== University faculties ==\nThe university currently has 24 colleges distributed in the governorates and sub-governoratesn, namely Shaqra, Huraymila, Al-Quwaiiyah, Al-Duwadimi, Sajir, Dhurma, Afif, Al-Muzahimiyah and Thadiq wa Mahmal. The colleges of Shaqra University are spread across a wide area of approximately {{cvt|400|sqkm}}.\n\n===Colleges at Shaqra University===\n<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Colleges at Shaqra University\n!Shaqra\n!Afif\n!Dhurma\n!\n|-\n|\n*College of Medicine\n* College of Computing and Information Technology\n* Community College\n* College of Applied Medical Sciences\n* College of Science and Humanities\n* College of Education\n|\n*College of Education\n* College of Business Administration\n|\n* College of Science and Humanities\n|\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Dawadmi\n!Huraymila\n!Al Quwaiiyah\n|\n|-\n|\n*College of Engineering\n* College of Education\n* College of Science and Humanities\n* Community College\n* Collage of Applied Medical Sciences\n* College of Pharmacy\n* College of Medicine\n|\n*The Community college (HCC)\n* College of Science and Humanities\n|<br />\n\n* College of Applied Medical Sciences\n* The Community College\n* College of Science and Humanities\n|\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Sajir\n!Thadq\n!Al Muzahimiyah\n|\n|-\n|\n* College of Science and Arts\n|\n* College of Science and Humanities\n|\n* College of Education\n|\n|}\n\n== Sports ==\nParticipated in the Gulf championship for universities known as \"The Eighth Sports Tournament for Universities and Institutions of Higher Education in the GCC Countries\" in November 2017<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2017-10-14|title=\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0627\u062a \u0648\u0645\u0624\u0633\u0633\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0644\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u064a \u0641\u064a \u062f\u0648\u0644 \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0648\u0646 \u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|url=https://ar.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A9_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%B6%D9%8A%D8%A9_%D9%84%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA_%D9%88%D9%85%D8%A4%D8%B3%D8%B3%D8%A7%D8%AA_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%85_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%8A_%D9%81%D9%8A_%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%84_%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%B3_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%88%D9%86_%D9%84%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%84_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9&oldid=25040688|journal=\u0648\u064a\u0643\u064a\u0628\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0627\u060c \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0633\u0648\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0629|language=ar}}</ref>\n\nAchieved a quantum leap in the performance indicator for universities since the university was ranked 21st last year, yet the university has been ranked 11th in the sports indicator for Saudi Universities among (31) universities and colleges.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://su.edu.sa Shaqra University Website]\n* [http://edugate.su.edu.sa/su/init Electronic services for students]\n{{coord missing|Saudi Arabia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shaqra University}}\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Saudi Arabia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Government university in Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Infobox university\n| image           = SHAQRA UNIVERSITY LOGO.png\n| caption         = \n| name            = Shaqra University\n| native_name     = \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0634\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0621\n| latin_name      = \n| motto           = \n| established     = 2009\n| type            = Government\n| calendar        = \n| endowment       = \n| staff           = \n| faculty         = \n| president       = [[Awad Alasmari]]\n| provost         = \n| principal       = \n| rector          = Awad_Alasmari\n| chancellor      = \n| vice_chancellor = \n| dean            = \n| head_label      = \n| head            = \n| students        = 32000\n| undergrad       = \n| postgrad        = \n| doctoral        = \n| city            = [[Shaqra]]\n| state           = [[Riyadh Province|Riyadh]]\n| country         = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| campus          = Multiple sites (spread across approx. 450 KM)\n| free_label      = \n| free            = \n| athletics       = \n| colors          = \n| mascot          = \n| nickname        = \n| affiliations    = \n| footnotes       = \n| website         = {{URL|su.edu.sa}}\n| address         = Main Campus, Al Duwadimi Road, Shaqra\n| telephone       = \n| coor            = \n| logo            = \n}}\n\n'''Shaqra University''' (SU) (Arabic: \u0634\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0621 \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 ) is located in [[Shaqra, Saudi Arabia]] ({{cvt|190|km}} northwest of [[Riyadh]]). It comes under the supervision of the Ministry of Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.4icu.org/reviews/13869.htm|title=Shaqra University {{!}} Ranking & Review|website=www.4icu.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mofa.gov.sa/sites/mofaen/ServicesAndInformation/news/MinistryNews/Pages/ArticleID2011723115950258.aspx|title=Saudi Ambassador to Australia and New Zealand Meets Dean of Shaqra University |agency= Kingdom of Saudi Arabia - Ministry of Foreign Affairs |website= www.mofa.gov.sa |language= en |access-date=2018-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/327384|title=King approves 4 new universities|date=2009-08-25|work=Arab News|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref> The University has twenty-four colleges in various disciplines. It is headquartered in Shaqra with its various colleges being geographically spread in the largest area of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia covering several governorates and sub-governorates lying in the west of Riyadh.\n\n== History ==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2018}}\nShaqra University was established on the 3rd of Ramadan 1430 (Gregorian date 24 August 2009), as per the decision of King Abdullah bin Abdulaziz Al Saud, the Prime Minister and the Chairman of the Higher Education Council, Saudi Arabia.\n\n== University faculties ==\nThe university currently has 24 colleges distributed in the governorates and sub-governoratesn, namely Shaqra, Huraymila, Al-Quwaiiyah, Al-Duwadimi, Sajir, Dhurma, Afif, Al-Muzahimiyah and Thadiq wa Mahmal. The colleges of Shaqra University are spread across a wide area of approximately {{cvt|400|sqkm}}.\n\n===Colleges===\n==== Shaqra ====\n\n* College of Medicine\n* College of Computing and Information Technology\n* Community College\n* College of Applied Medical Sciences\n* College of Science and Humanities\n* College of Education\n\n==== Afif ====\n\n* College of Education\n* College of Business Administration\n\n==== Dhurma ====\n\n* College of Science and Humanities\n\n==== Dawadmi ====\n\n* College of Engineering\n* College of Education\n* College of Science and Humanities\n* Community College\n* Collage of Applied Medical Sciences\n* College of Pharmacy\n* College of Medicine\n\n==== Huraymila ====\n\n* The Community college (HCC)\n* College of Science and Humanities\n\n==== Al Quwaiiyah ====\n\n* College of Applied Medical Sciences\n* The Community College\n* College of Science and Humanities\n\n==== Sajir ====\n\n* College of Science and Arts\n\n==== Thadq ====\n\n* College of Science and Humanities\n\n==== Al Muzahimiyah ====\n\n* College of Education\n\n== Sports ==\nParticipated in the Gulf championship for universities known as \"The Eighth Sports Tournament for Universities and Institutions of Higher Education in the GCC Countries\" in November 2017<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2017-10-14|title=\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0627\u062a \u0648\u0645\u0624\u0633\u0633\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0644\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u064a \u0641\u064a \u062f\u0648\u0644 \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0648\u0646 \u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|url=https://ar.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A9_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%B6%D9%8A%D8%A9_%D9%84%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA_%D9%88%D9%85%D8%A4%D8%B3%D8%B3%D8%A7%D8%AA_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%85_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%8A_%D9%81%D9%8A_%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%84_%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%84%D8%B3_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%88%D9%86_%D9%84%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%84_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9&oldid=25040688|journal=\u0648\u064a\u0643\u064a\u0628\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0627\u060c \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0633\u0648\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0629|language=ar}}</ref>\n\nAchieved a quantum leap in the performance indicator for universities since the university was ranked 21st last year, yet the university has been ranked 11th in the sports indicator for Saudi Universities among (31) universities and colleges.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://su.edu.sa Shaqra University Website]\n* [http://edugate.su.edu.sa/su/init Electronic services for students]\n{{coord missing|Saudi Arabia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shaqra University}}\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Saudi Arabia]]\n", "name_user": "Susaed", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eColleges:List updated with proper formatting)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaqra_University"}
{"title_page": "Waterbury, Vermont", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Waterbury, Vermont\n|settlement_type          = [[New England town|Town]]\n|nickname                 =\n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Waterbury VT.JPG\n|imagesize                =\n|image_caption            = Downtown Waterbury\n|image_flag               =\n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = Washington County Vermont Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Waterbury highlighted.svg\n|map_caption              = Location in Washington County and the state of Vermont\n| pushpin_map = USA\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in the United States\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Vermont]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Vermont|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Washington County, Vermont|Washington]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     =\n|government_type          =\n|leader_title             =\n|leader_name              =\n|leader_title1            =\n|leader_name1             =\n|established_title        =\n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_magnitude           =\n|area_total_km2           = 128.8\n|area_land_km2            = 124.9\n|area_water_km2           = 3.9\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 49.7\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 48.2\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 1.5\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     =\n|population_total         = 5064\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      =\n|elevation_m              = 187\n|elevation_ft             = 614\n|coordinates              = {{coord|44|20|15|N|72|45|20|W|region:US-VT_type:city(4915)|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]s\n|postal_code              = 05671, 05676 ,05677\n|area_code                = [[Area code 802|802]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 50-76975<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1462244<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|www.waterburyvt.com}}\n|footnotes                =\n}}\n\n'''Waterbury''' is a [[New England town|town]] in [[Washington County, Vermont|Washington County]] in central [[Vermont]], United States. It is also the name of a [[Waterbury (village), Vermont|village]] within that town.  The population of the town was 5,064 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html| url-status=dead| archive-date=February 12, 2020| title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (DP-1): Waterbury town, Washington County, Vermont| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=September 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/waterburytownwashingtoncountyvermont/AGE765210|title=Waterbury; 2010 Census|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=September 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe location where Waterbury now lies was once the frontier between the [[Mahican]] and [[Pennacook]] people. European settlement of the area dates from 1763, when King [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]] granted a charter for land in the [[Winooski River]] valley. James Marsh became the first permanent white settler in the region in 1783. Many of the early settlers came from [[Waterbury, Connecticut|Waterbury]], [[Connecticut]], and named their new town in honor of the hometown.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}} The village of Waterbury was incorporated in 1882 with a population of over 2,000.\n\nThe [[Central Vermont Railroad]] came to Waterbury in 1849.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greatamericanstations.com/stations/waterbury-vt-wab/|title=Waterbury, VT (WAB)|work=Great American Stations|access-date=2017-03-03|language=en-US}}</ref> The railroad expanded a passenger station for the railroad in 1875, making the station a more major stop on the Vermonter.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[Green Mountain Seminary]] was built in Waterbury Center in 1869.\n\nThe state opened the Vermont State Asylum for the Insane here in 1891.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.crjc.org/heritage/V02-34.htm|title=Brattleboro Retreat (Vermont Asylum for the Insane)|last=Sanders|first=Stephen|date=1984-04-12|website=www.crjc.org|access-date=2008-05-13}}</ref> The hospital, renamed the [[Vermont State Hospital]], grew to occupy over 40 buildings, but by the 1980s the number of patients had declined to the point where only one building was required. The remainder of the campus came to be used for state offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.central-vt.com/towns/history/HstWate.htm|title=History of Waterbury|website=www.central-vt.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415085209/http://www.central-vt.com/towns/history/HstWate.htm|archive-date=2012-04-15|url-status=dead|access-date=2011-10-17}}</ref>\n \nLike many [[New England]] towns, Waterbury's economy was based around the local river mill industry and the surrounding agricultural producers. The mills produced products such as [[lumber]] and finished wood products, wicker products, leather, starch, and alcohol. The agriculture was based on [[sheep husbandry|sheep]] through the 19th century but switched over to [[dairy farming]] by the 20th century. Waterbury had a ski factory in the 1940s, the Derby & Ball Company.\n\nIn 1927, Waterbury, like many other Vermont communities, was devastated by [[flood]]ing. Inscriptions on the sides of some buildings in Waterbury village purport to show where the level of the water rose during the [[Great Vermont Flood of 1927|1927 flood]]. The village recovered, and in 1938 the [[Waterbury Dam]] was built on the Little River by the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] to control future flooding in areas downstream of the town center.\n\nOn August 29, 2011, [[Hurricane Irene|Tropical Storm Irene]] flooded downtown Waterbury and filled the buildings of the [[Vermont State Hospital]], Vermont's public psychiatric complex, with up to {{convert|6|ft}} of water. Patients from the mental hospital were temporarily housed in various locations around Vermont, and over 1,100 of the 1,586 state employees were working in office space in other towns as of October 2011. The state was expected to decide by 2012 whether to relocate all or part of the workforce back to Waterbury.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://vtdigger.org/2011/09/15/state-begins-post-irene-move-of-more-than-1100-state-employees/|title=State begins post-Irene move of more than 1,100 state employees|last=Nemethy|first=Andrew|date=2011-09-15|work=VTDigger|access-date=2011-10-17|language=en-US}}</ref>{{Update inline|date=April 2018}}\n\n==Economy==\n[[Image:Ben&JarrysWaterbury.jpg|240px|thumb|left|A sign leading to [[Ben & Jerry's]] Ice Cream factory in Waterbury]]\nWaterbury is the location of [[Ben & Jerry's]] Ice Cream, whose factory tours have become Vermont's most popular [[tourist attraction]].<ref>[http://www.vtliving.com/attractions/benjerrys/index.shtml Attractions - Ben Jerrys] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610015643/http://www.vtliving.com/attractions/benjerrys/index.shtml |date=2013-06-10 }}. VTLiving.com. Retrieved on 2014-04-12.</ref> \n<!---This is not supposed to be a general list of every business in town, just the most prominent ones, ones that are known outside the area. Please respect this, smaller businesses have their own websites for promotion purposes and are not of an encyclopedic interest.--->\nOther local businesses include: [[SunCommon]], [http://www.henofthewood.com Hen of the Wood Restaurant], [[Cabot Creamery]] Annex, the Alchemist microbrewery, Cold Hollow Cider Mill, [[Green Mountain Coffee Roasters]], and [[Lake Champlain Chocolates]], as well as several well-reputed bars and restaurants. Businesses in the town, which sits between several major mountains including [[Mount Mansfield]], typically thrive during the month of October, when tourism swells thanks to [[fall foliage]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1800= 644\n|1810= 966\n|1820= 1269\n|1830= 1650\n|1840= 1992\n|1850= 2352\n|1860= 2198\n|1870= 2633\n|1880= 2297\n|1890= 2232\n|1900= 2810\n|1910= 3273\n|1920= 3542\n|1930= 4045\n|1940= 4118\n|1950= 4276\n|1960= 4303\n|1970= 4614\n|1980= 4465\n|1990= 4589\n|2000= 4915\n|2010= 5064\n|estyear=2015\n|estimate=5112\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2015/SUB-EST2015.html|title=Annual Estimates of the Resident Population for Incorporated Places: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2016|archive-url=https://archive.today/20160602200744/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2015/SUB-EST2015.html|archive-date=June 2, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"VTHistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vermonthistory.org/explorer|title=Vermont History Explorer|accessdate=August 7, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 4,915 people, 2,011 households, and 1,321 families residing in the town.  The [[population density]] was 810.4 people per square mile (312.9/km\u00b2).  There were 2,106 housing units at an average density of 347.2 per square mile (134.1/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the town was 97.80% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.26% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.12% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.65% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.26% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.89% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.67% of the population.\n\nThere were 2,011 households out of which 24.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 54.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.3% were non-families. 25.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.42 and the average family size was 2.93.\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 25.1% under the age of 18, 5.5% from 18 to 24, 32.8% from 25 to 44, 26.2% from 45 to 64, and 10.3% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 37.7 years. For every 100 females, there were 97.4 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 93.4 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the town was $44,940, and the median income for a family was $60,547. Males had a median income of $35,566 versus $25,838 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $25,858.  About 3.3% of families and 6.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 7.0% of those under age 18 and 4.9% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Government and infrastructure==\nThe State of Vermont operates the Waterbury Office Complex.<ref>\"[http://doc.vermont.gov/about/map/view Waterbury State Office Complex] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100825064732/http://doc.vermont.gov/about/map/view |date=2010-08-25 }}.\" [[Vermont Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on December 7, 2009.</ref> The [[Vermont Department of Corrections]] has its headquarters in the Waterbury Office Complex.<ref>\"[http://www.doc.state.vt.us/about/contact-us/ Contact the Vermont Department of Corrections].\" [[Vermont Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on December 7, 2009.</ref><ref>\"[http://doc.vermont.gov/about About the Department of Corrections].\" [[Vermont Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on December 7, 2009.\"A map showing where the Department of Corrections Central Office is in the Waterbury State Office complex.\"</ref>\n\n==Education==\nWaterbury belongs to the Washington West Supervisory Union. Students attend Thatcher Brook Primary School for grades preschool and Kindergarten through 4th grade, Crossett Brook Middle School for grades 5\u20138, and [[Harwood Union High School]] for grades 9\u201312.\n\n==Transportation==\n{{See also|Waterbury (Amtrak station)}}\n[[Amtrak]], the national passenger rail system, provides daily service to Waterbury, operating its ''[[Vermonter (train)|Vermonter]]'' between [[St. Albans (town), Vermont|St. Albans]] and [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\nThe Green Mountain Transit Agency (GMTA) provides public transit bus services to [[Burlington, Vermont|Burlington]], [[Montpelier, Vermont|Montpelier]], [[Morrisville, Vermont|Morrisville]], and [[Stowe, Vermont|Stowe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ridegmt.com/regions/stowelamoille/|title=Stowe/Lamoille|website=ridegmt.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref>\n\nWaterbury is served by [[Interstate 89]], [[U.S. Route 2 in Vermont|U.S. Route 2]], and [[Vermont Route 100|Route 100]].\n\n==Media==\nRadio station [[WDEV]]&nbsp;-550 AM & 96.1 FM (News/Talk), is located in town, with its offices and studios on Stowe Street. [[WWMP]]&nbsp;(Rock 103.3) \u2013 103.3 FM (Mainstream rock) is officially licensed to Waterbury and has its transmission tower located on Ricker Mountain (which it shares with sister station [[WNCS]] Montpelier), but its offices and studios are located in [[South Burlington, Vermont|South Burlington]].\n\n[https://www.vtcng.com/waterbury_record/ The Waterbury Record] was a weekly newspaper that served the local area. On March 26, 2020, the Vermont Community Newspaper Group announced that it was suspending publication of the Waterbury Record, citing the lack of widespread advertising support and now the economic impact of the coronavirus pandemic. The March 26 issue will be the last one, after 13 years of publication.<ref>{{cite news |title=Waterbury Record publishes its last issue |url=https://www.vtcng.com/waterbury_record/news/local_news/waterbury-record-publishes-its-last-issue/article_3900c10a-6f63-11ea-9691-0353b50d5eaf.html |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Waterbury Record |publisher=Vermont Community Newspaper Group |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n<!-- Note:\n\u00b7 Only people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here. This establishes notability.\n\u00b7 The article must mention how they are associated with Waterbury, whether born, raised, or residing.\n\u00b7 The fact of their association should have a reliable source cited.\n\u00b7 Alphabetical by last name please.\n\u00b7 All others will be deleted.\n-->\n\n* [[Charles J. Adams (Vermont Attorney General)|Charles J. Adams]], [[Vermont Attorney General]]<ref>{{cite news |date=May 17, 2008 |title=Obituary, Charles J. Adams |url=http://www.timesargus.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080517/OBITUARIES/805170339/-1/RSS14 |newspaper=Times Argus |location=Barre, VT |access-date=November 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105224625/http://www.timesargus.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20080517%2FOBITUARIES%2F805170339%2F-1%2FRSS14 |archive-date=November 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Harold D. Campbell]], Major general in the [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] during [[World War II]]\n* [[William P. Dillingham]], 42nd [[List of Governors of Vermont|Governor of Vermont]]\n* [[Wallace M. Greene]], commandant of the Marine Corps\n* [[Henry Janes]], soldier, humanitarian and chief surgeon at [[Battle of Gettysburg|Gettysburg]]\n* [[Ken Squier]], [[NASCAR]] commentator for [[CBS]], owner of [[WDEV]] Radio and co-owner of the [[Thunder Road International SpeedBowl]] auto-racing track in [[Barre (town), Vermont|Barre]]\n* [[William Wells (general)|William Wells]], merchant, Civil War general and Medal of Honor recipient\n\n==Climate==\nThis [[climate|climatic]] region is typified by large seasonal temperature differences, with warm to hot (and often humid) summers that are known to occasionally reach 90 to 100 degrees and cold (sometimes severely cold) winters.  According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Waterbury has a [[humid continental climate]], abbreviated \"Dfb\" on climate maps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=518834&cityname=Waterbury,+Vermont,+United+States+of+America&units=|title=Waterbury, Vermont K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification (Weatherbase)|website=Weatherbase|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Waterbury, Vermont}}\n* [http://www.waterburyvt.com/ Town of Waterbury official website]\n* [http://www.WaterburyPublicLibrary.com Waterbury Public Library]\n\n{{Washington County, Vermont}}\n{{Vermont}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Waterbury, Vermont| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Washington County, Vermont]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Waterbury, Vermont\n|settlement_type          = [[New England town|Town]]\n|nickname                 =\n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Waterbury VT.JPG\n|imagesize                =\n|image_caption            = Downtown Waterbury\n|image_flag               =\n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = Washington County Vermont Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Waterbury highlighted.svg\n|map_caption              = Location in Washington County and the state of Vermont\n| pushpin_map = USA\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in the United States\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Vermont]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Vermont|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Washington County, Vermont|Washington]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     =\n|government_type          =\n|leader_title             =\n|leader_name              =\n|leader_title1            =\n|leader_name1             =\n|established_title        =\n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_magnitude           =\n|area_total_km2           = 128.8\n|area_land_km2            = 124.9\n|area_water_km2           = 3.9\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 49.7\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 48.2\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 1.5\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     =\n|population_total         = 5064\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      =\n|elevation_m              = 187\n|elevation_ft             = 614\n|coordinates              = {{coord|44|20|15|N|72|45|20|W|region:US-VT_type:city(4915)|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]s\n|postal_code              = 05671, 05676 ,05677\n|area_code                = [[Area code 802|802]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 50-76975<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1462244<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|www.waterburyvt.com}}\n|footnotes                =\n}}\n\n'''Waterbury''' is a [[New England town|town]] in [[Washington County, Vermont|Washington County]] in central [[Vermont]], United States. It is also the name of a [[Waterbury (village), Vermont|village]] within that town.  The population of the town was 5,064 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html| url-status=dead| archive-date=February 12, 2020| title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (DP-1): Waterbury town, Washington County, Vermont| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=September 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/waterburytownwashingtoncountyvermont/AGE765210|title=Waterbury; 2010 Census|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=September 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe location where Waterbury now lies was once the frontier between the [[Mahican]] and [[Pennacook]] people. European settlement of the area dates from 1763, when King [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]] granted a charter for land in the [[Winooski River]] valley. James Marsh became the first permanent white settler in the region in 1783. Many of the early settlers came from [[Waterbury, Connecticut|Waterbury]], [[Connecticut]], and named their new town in honor of the hometown.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}} The village of Waterbury was incorporated in 1882 with a population of over 2,000.\n\nThe [[Central Vermont Railroad]] came to Waterbury in 1849.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.greatamericanstations.com/stations/waterbury-vt-wab/|title=Waterbury, VT (WAB)|work=Great American Stations|access-date=2017-03-03|language=en-US}}</ref> The railroad expanded a passenger station for the railroad in 1875, making the station a more major stop on the Vermonter.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[Green Mountain Seminary]] was built in Waterbury Center in 1869.\n\nThe state opened the Vermont State Asylum for the Insane here in 1891.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.crjc.org/heritage/V02-34.htm|title=Brattleboro Retreat (Vermont Asylum for the Insane)|last=Sanders|first=Stephen|date=1984-04-12|website=www.crjc.org|access-date=2008-05-13}}</ref> The hospital, renamed the [[Vermont State Hospital]], grew to occupy over 40 buildings, but by the 1980s the number of patients had declined to the point where only one building was required. The remainder of the campus came to be used for state offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.central-vt.com/towns/history/HstWate.htm|title=History of Waterbury|website=www.central-vt.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415085209/http://www.central-vt.com/towns/history/HstWate.htm|archive-date=2012-04-15|url-status=dead|access-date=2011-10-17}}</ref>\n \nLike many [[New England]] towns, Waterbury's economy was based around the local river mill industry and the surrounding agricultural producers. The mills produced products such as [[lumber]] and finished wood products, wicker products, leather, starch, and alcohol. The agriculture was based on [[sheep husbandry|sheep]] through the 19th century but switched over to [[dairy farming]] by the 20th century. Waterbury had a ski factory in the 1940s, the Derby & Ball Company.\n\nIn 1927, Waterbury, like many other Vermont communities, was devastated by [[flood]]ing. Inscriptions on the sides of some buildings in Waterbury village purport to show where the level of the water rose during the [[Great Vermont Flood of 1927|1927 flood]]. The village recovered, and in 1938 the [[Waterbury Dam]] was built on the Little River by the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] to control future flooding in areas downstream of the town center.\n\nOn August 29, 2011, [[Hurricane Irene|Tropical Storm Irene]] flooded downtown Waterbury and filled the buildings of the [[Vermont State Hospital]], Vermont's public psychiatric complex, with up to {{convert|6|ft}} of water. Patients from the mental hospital were temporarily housed in various locations around Vermont, and over 1,100 of the 1,586 state employees were working in office space in other towns as of October 2011. The state was expected to decide by 2012 whether to relocate all or part of the workforce back to Waterbury.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://vtdigger.org/2011/09/15/state-begins-post-irene-move-of-more-than-1100-state-employees/|title=State begins post-Irene move of more than 1,100 state employees|last=Nemethy|first=Andrew|date=2011-09-15|work=VTDigger|access-date=2011-10-17|language=en-US}}</ref>{{Update inline|date=April 2018}}\n\n==Economy==\n[[Image:Ben&JarrysWaterbury.jpg|240px|thumb|left|A sign leading to [[Ben & Jerry's]] Ice Cream factory in Waterbury]]\nWaterbury is the location of [[Ben & Jerry's]] Ice Cream, whose factory tours have become Vermont's most popular [[tourist attraction]].<ref>[http://www.vtliving.com/attractions/benjerrys/index.shtml Attractions - Ben Jerrys] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610015643/http://www.vtliving.com/attractions/benjerrys/index.shtml |date=2013-06-10 }}. VTLiving.com. Retrieved on 2014-04-12.</ref> \n<!---This is not supposed to be a general list of every business in town, just the most prominent ones, ones that are known outside the area. Please respect this, smaller businesses have their own websites for promotion purposes and are not of an encyclopedic interest.--->\nOther local businesses include: [[SunCommon]], [http://www.henofthewood.com Hen of the Wood Restaurant], [[Cabot Creamery]] Annex, the Alchemist microbrewery, Cold Hollow Cider Mill, [[Green Mountain Coffee Roasters]], and [[Lake Champlain Chocolates]], as well as several well-reputed bars and restaurants. Businesses in the town, which sits between several major mountains including [[Mount Mansfield]], typically thrive during the month of October, when tourism swells thanks to [[fall foliage]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1800= 644\n|1810= 966\n|1820= 1269\n|1830= 1650\n|1840= 1992\n|1850= 2352\n|1860= 2198\n|1870= 2633\n|1880= 2297\n|1890= 2232\n|1900= 2810\n|1910= 3273\n|1920= 3542\n|1930= 4045\n|1940= 4118\n|1950= 4276\n|1960= 4303\n|1970= 4614\n|1980= 4465\n|1990= 4589\n|2000= 4915\n|2010= 5064\n|estyear=2015\n|estimate=5112\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2015/SUB-EST2015.html|title=Annual Estimates of the Resident Population for Incorporated Places: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2016|archive-url=https://archive.today/20160602200744/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2015/SUB-EST2015.html|archive-date=June 2, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"VTHistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vermonthistory.org/explorer|title=Vermont History Explorer|accessdate=August 7, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 4,915 people, 2,011 households, and 1,321 families residing in the town.  The [[population density]] was 810.4 people per square mile (312.9/km\u00b2).  There were 2,106 housing units at an average density of 347.2 per square mile (134.1/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the town was 97.80% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.26% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.12% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.65% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.26% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.89% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.67% of the population.\n\nThere were 2,011 households out of which 24.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 54.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.3% were non-families. 25.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.42 and the average family size was 2.93.\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 25.1% under the age of 18, 5.5% from 18 to 24, 32.8% from 25 to 44, 26.2% from 45 to 64, and 10.3% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 37.7 years. For every 100 females, there were 97.4 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 93.4 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the town was $44,940, and the median income for a family was $60,547. Males had a median income of $35,566 versus $25,838 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $25,858.  About 3.3% of families and 6.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 7.0% of those under age 18 and 4.9% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Government and infrastructure==\nThe State of Vermont operates the Waterbury Office Complex.<ref>\"[http://doc.vermont.gov/about/map/view Waterbury State Office Complex] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100825064732/http://doc.vermont.gov/about/map/view |date=2010-08-25 }}.\" [[Vermont Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on December 7, 2009.</ref> The [[Vermont Department of Corrections]] has its headquarters in the Waterbury Office Complex.<ref>\"[http://www.doc.state.vt.us/about/contact-us/ Contact the Vermont Department of Corrections].\" [[Vermont Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on December 7, 2009.</ref><ref>\"[http://doc.vermont.gov/about About the Department of Corrections].\" [[Vermont Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on December 7, 2009.\"A map showing where the Department of Corrections Central Office is in the Waterbury State Office complex.\"</ref>\n\n==Education==\nWaterbury belongs to the Washington West Supervisory Union. Students attend Thatcher Brook Primary School for grades preschool and Kindergarten through 4th grade, Crossett Brook Middle School for grades 5\u20138, and [[Harwood Union High School]] for grades 9\u201312.\n\n==Transportation==\n{{See also|Waterbury (Amtrak station)}}\n[[Amtrak]], the national passenger rail system, provides daily service to Waterbury, operating its ''[[Vermonter (train)|Vermonter]]'' between [[St. Albans (town), Vermont|St. Albans]] and [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\nThe Green Mountain Transit Agency (GMTA) provides public transit bus services to [[Burlington, Vermont|Burlington]], [[Montpelier, Vermont|Montpelier]], [[Morrisville, Vermont|Morrisville]], and [[Stowe, Vermont|Stowe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ridegmt.com/regions/stowelamoille/|title=Stowe/Lamoille|website=ridegmt.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref>\n\nWaterbury is served by [[Interstate 89]], [[U.S. Route 2 in Vermont|U.S. Route 2]], and [[Vermont Route 100|Route 100]].\n\n==Media==\nRadio station [[WDEV]]&nbsp;-550 AM & 96.1 FM (News/Talk), is located in town, with its offices and studios on Stowe Street. [[WWMP]]&nbsp;(Rock 103.3) \u2013 103.3 FM (Mainstream rock) is officially licensed to Waterbury and has its transmission tower located on Ricker Mountain (which it shares with sister station [[WNCS]] Montpelier), but its offices and studios are located in [[South Burlington, Vermont|South Burlington]].\n\n[https://www.vtcng.com/waterbury_record/ The Waterbury Record] was a weekly newspaper that serves the local area. On March 26, 2020, the Vermont Community Newspaper Group announced that it was suspending publication of the Waterbury Record, citing the lack of widespread advertising support and now the economic impact of the coronavirus pandemic. The March 26 issue will be the last one, after 13 years of publication.<ref>{{cite news |title=Waterbury Record publishes its last issue |url=https://www.vtcng.com/waterbury_record/news/local_news/waterbury-record-publishes-its-last-issue/article_3900c10a-6f63-11ea-9691-0353b50d5eaf.html |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Waterbury Record |publisher=Vermont Community Newspaper Group |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n<!-- Note:\n\u00b7 Only people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here. This establishes notability.\n\u00b7 The article must mention how they are associated with Waterbury, whether born, raised, or residing.\n\u00b7 The fact of their association should have a reliable source cited.\n\u00b7 Alphabetical by last name please.\n\u00b7 All others will be deleted.\n-->\n\n* [[Charles J. Adams (Vermont Attorney General)|Charles J. Adams]], [[Vermont Attorney General]]<ref>{{cite news |date=May 17, 2008 |title=Obituary, Charles J. Adams |url=http://www.timesargus.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080517/OBITUARIES/805170339/-1/RSS14 |newspaper=Times Argus |location=Barre, VT |access-date=November 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105224625/http://www.timesargus.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20080517%2FOBITUARIES%2F805170339%2F-1%2FRSS14 |archive-date=November 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Harold D. Campbell]], Major general in the [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] during [[World War II]]\n* [[William P. Dillingham]], 42nd [[List of Governors of Vermont|Governor of Vermont]]\n* [[Wallace M. Greene]], commandant of the Marine Corps\n* [[Henry Janes]], soldier, humanitarian and chief surgeon at [[Battle of Gettysburg|Gettysburg]]\n* [[Ken Squier]], [[NASCAR]] commentator for [[CBS]], owner of [[WDEV]] Radio and co-owner of the [[Thunder Road International SpeedBowl]] auto-racing track in [[Barre (town), Vermont|Barre]]\n* [[William Wells (general)|William Wells]], merchant, Civil War general and Medal of Honor recipient\n\n==Climate==\nThis [[climate|climatic]] region is typified by large seasonal temperature differences, with warm to hot (and often humid) summers that are known to occasionally reach 90 to 100 degrees and cold (sometimes severely cold) winters.  According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Waterbury has a [[humid continental climate]], abbreviated \"Dfb\" on climate maps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=518834&cityname=Waterbury,+Vermont,+United+States+of+America&units=|title=Waterbury, Vermont K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification (Weatherbase)|website=Weatherbase|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Waterbury, Vermont}}\n* [http://www.waterburyvt.com/ Town of Waterbury official website]\n* [http://www.WaterburyPublicLibrary.com Waterbury Public Library]\n\n{{Washington County, Vermont}}\n{{Vermont}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Waterbury, Vermont| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Washington County, Vermont]]\n", "name_user": "Dyork", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMedia:Corrected tense of a verb", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waterbury,_Vermont"}
{"title_page": "Hamiduzzaman Khan", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2017}}\n{{infobox person\n|name = Hamiduzzaman Khan \n|native_name=\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09bf\u09a6\u09c1\u099c\u09cd\u099c\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09a8 \u0996\u09be\u09a8\n|native_name_lang=bn\n|image=Hamiduzzam Khan.png\n|birth_date = {{birth year and age|1946}}\n|nationality=Bangladeshi\n|occupation=Sculptor\n|awards=[[#Awards|full list]]\n|birth_place = [[Kishoreganj]], [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]]\n|alma_mater = [[University of Dhaka]] <br/> [[Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda]] \n}}\n\n'''Hamiduzzaman Khan''' (born {{circa|1946}}) is a Bangladeshi sculptor.<ref name=dhakaart>{{cite web|url=http://dhakaartcenter.org/artist_directory/Hamiduzzaman_Khan.html|title=Hamiduzzaman Khan|publisher=Dhaka Art Center|accessdate=June 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKhan was born in 1946 in [[Kishoreganj District]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/exhibition/hamiduzzaman-khan-retrospective-opens-bnm-1482982|title=Hamiduzzaman Khan Retrospective opens at BNM|date=2017-10-29|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref> In 1962 he completed [[matriculation]] and got admitted into the erstwhile East Pakistan College of Arts and Crafts (now [[Faculty of Fine Arts, University of Dhaka]]). At the College of Arts and Crafts, he studied under the guidance of artists [[Zainul Abedin]], [[Safiuddin Ahmed]], [[Aminul Islam (artist)|Aminul Islam]], [[Mustafa Manwar]]. He earned [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] in 1967, graduating in painting. Khan was awarded an Indian government scholarship in 1973 to study for a [[Master of Fine Arts]] degree. He then went on to study at the [[University of Baroda Faculty of Fine Arts|Faculty of Fine Arts, Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda]], earning his master's degree in 1976.<ref name=dhakaart/> At Baroda, he studied in the tutelage of artists Raghav Kaneria, Mahendra Pandia, [[K. G. Subramanyan]]. <ref name=StarMag>{{Cite news |date=2010-10-10 |title=Symbolising Freedom |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/magazine/2010/12/02/art.htm |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nWhile a student at the College of Arts and Crafts, Khan experienced a road accident that fractured his skull, causing him to have a [[reconstructive surgery]] in the head. As there was no facility for the surgery in Dhaka, he was advised to receive treatment from the [[Royal Infirmary of Edinburgh]] in Scotland. On his way to Scotland by ship, Khan was impressed by seeing traditional African carvings in [[Dakar]] at a stopover. Following the surgery, he visited the [[British Museum]], [[Victoria and Albert Museum]], [[National Gallery]], [[Tate Galleries]].<ref name=MasterStroke>{{Cite news |date=2008-03-19 |title=Master Stroke |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-28335 |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> In British Museum, Khan studied [[mummies]], statues from Greek, Egyptian and Roman times. Khan was particularly fascinated by sculptures in public places and the impact sculptures had in civic life. He was impressed by [[Henry Moore]]'s sculptures. In Italy, he experienced sculptures by [[Michelangelo]] at [[St. Peter's Basilica]] and in Paris, he saw artworks at the [[Louvre]]. Sculptures by [[Alberto Giacometti]] in Paris and [[Laoco\u00f6n and His Sons]] have had a lasting impact in his mind.<ref name=MasterStroke/> The experiences in Europe inspired Khan to study and focus his efforts on sculpture.<ref name=StarMag/><ref name=Jamini>{{Cite news |date=2013-10-13 |title=An Interview with Hamiduzzaman Khan |url=https://issuu.com/bengal-foundation/docs/jamini/8 |work=Jamini|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nDuring his stay in [[Baroda]] as a student, Khan made sculpture based on the [[Bangladesh War of Liberation]] and presented it to viewers in his first exhibit. The sculpture was a massacred human figure in lying position. Khan was praised by artist [[M. F. Husain]] and he was awarded first prize for the work in the exhibition celebrating twenty-five years of Faculty of Fine Arts, University of Baroda.\n\n==Career==\nKhan participated in his first national sculpture exhibition in 1976, and was awarded the first prize for his sculpture \"Dorja\"(door). He was appointed to make a bronze sculpture in Bangabhaban in 1981, entitled \"Bird Family\".\n\nIn the 1980s Khan was commissioned to decorate the [[Bangabhaban]] fountain with sculptural work.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2012-06-10 |title=Hamiduzzaman Khan's Solo Exhibition at Galleri Kaya: Watercolours and Sculptures Exposition |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2682859231.html |url-status=dead |work=Dhaka Courier |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414135727/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2682859231.html |archive-date=2016-04-14}}</ref> He created a bronze sculpture in Bangabhaban in 1981, entitled \"Bird Family\". In 1982, Khan's sculpture exhibition about the War of Independence was held at the Faculty of Fine Arts.  His sculpture \"Steps\" was installed in 1988 in the Olympic Park in Seoul, South Korea.<ref name=way>[http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMD6KG_The_Steps_5066851221_Olympic_Park__Seoul_Korea \"The Steps (\uc5ec\uc815) - Olympic Park  -  Seoul, Korea - Abstract Public Sculptures on Waymarking.com\"].</ref> In 1990, he placed a figurative sculpture, based on a fighter at the War of Liberation with one leg and arm amputed and a riffle on the other hand, the \"Samsaptak\" in the arena of Jahangirnagar University.\n\nKhan has created many paintings and sculptures while travelling abroad, including India, Korea<ref name=way /> and the United States. In 2015, he continued to exhibit his work and to conduct workshops.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://daily-sun.com/magazine/details/55568/JOLERDHARA|title=Jolerdhara|last=Sun|first=The Daily|work=Daily Sun|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n===Solo===\n* ''An Indigenous Minimalist'', Bengal Gallery of Fine Art, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2002).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2002-10-16 |title=An Indigenous Minimalist |url=https://bengalfoundation.org/reviews_archive/an-indigenous-minimalist/ |url-status= |work=Bengal Foundation |access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=bf>{{cite web|url=https://bengalfoundation.org/featured_artist/hamiduzzaman-khan/|title=Hamiduzzaman Khan|publisher=Bengal Foundation|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Homage to Matter'', [[British Council Bangladesh|The British Council]], Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2006).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2006-12-09 |title=Homage to Matter: A Garden by Hamiduzzaman Khan |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/2006/12/09/d612091401105.htm |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Recent Sculpture and Other Works'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2006).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2006-02-19 |title=\u2019Recent Sculpture and Other Works\u2019 |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/2006/02/19/d60219140199.htm |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''The Intimate World of Colour'', Gallery of Fine Art, [[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]], Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2008).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2008-08-24 |title=The Hamiduzzaman experience |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-51541 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Nocturnal Shades'', Bengal Gallery of Fine Arts, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2010).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2010-05-10 |title=Nocturnal Shades |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/magazine/2010/05/02/art.htm |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Time and Beyond'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2010).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2010-12-04 |title=Solo exhibition of Hamiduzzaman begins today |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-164698 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Watercolours & Sculptures'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2012).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2012-05-23 |title=Hamiduzzaman Khan\u2019s solo exhibition to open at Galleri Kaya |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-235257 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Earthly Treasures'', Athena Gallery, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2014).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2014-03-09 |title=Highlighting botanical and human forms |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/highlighting-botanical-and-human-forms-14657 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Stones'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2014).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2014-11-07 |title=Hamiduzzaman\u2019s exhibition till Nov 12 |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-in-brief-49158 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Stones-2'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2016).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2016-03-05 |title=Hamiduzzaman opens solo exhibit on 70th birthday |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/hamiduzzaman-opens-solo-exhibit-70th-birthday-786628 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Of Watercolours, Boats and Faces'', Shilpangan Gallery, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2016).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2016-09-26 |title=Hamiduzzaman\u2019s art show begins Sept 30 |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/61513 |url-status= |work=The Independent|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Jiban Annashane'', [[Institute of Architects Bangladesh]], Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2017).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-01-09 |title=Many shades of life under spotlight |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/exhibition/many-shades-life-under-spotlight-1342303 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Hamiduzzaman Khan Retrospective'', Nalinikanta Bhattashali Gallery, [[Bangladesh National Museum]], Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2017).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-10-28 |title=Hamiduzzaman Khan retrospective underway |url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/27148/hamiduzzaman-khan-retrospective-underway |url-status= |work=[[New Age (Bangladesh)|New Age]]|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-10-28 |title=Inauguration of Hamiduzzaman Khan's retrospective at BNM |url=https://www.bnm.gov.bd/bnmtoday/2017/10/30/inauguration-of-hamiduzzaman-khans-retrospective-at-bnm/ |work=[[Bangladesh National Museum]]|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n* ''Nocurnal Shades'', Abinta Gallery of Fine Arts, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2018).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-11-21 |title=Hamiduzzaman Khan celebrates diversity |url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/56634/hamiduzzaman-khan-celebrates-diversity |url-status= |work=[[New Age|New Age (Bangladesh)]]|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-12-24 |title=Hamiduzzaman Khan\u2019s mastery over pure-abstraction |url=https://www.observerbd.com/details.php?id=174659 |url-status= |work=The Daily Observer|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* Display of Early Watercolours by Hamiduzzaman Khan, Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2018).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2019-06-10 |title=A treasure trove brought back home |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/news/treasure-trove-brought-back-home-1759447 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Feeling the Void'', Dwip Gallery, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2019).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2019-10-06 |title=Hamiduzzaman Khan\u2019s \u2018Feeling the Void\u2019 on October 11 |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/arcprint/details/218259/2019-10-06 |url-status= |work=[[ The Independent|The Independent (Bangladesh)]]|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n===Group===\n* ''Exhibition at Olympic Sculpture Park'', [[Seoul Olympic Park]], Seoul, Republic of Korea, (1988).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-07-04 |title=Young sculptors are doing good |url=https://www.newagebd.net/print/article/19024 |url-status= |work=[[New Age (Bangladesh)|New Age]]|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2007-12-08 |title=Images of an artist's life |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-14606 |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n* ''Soft Reflections'', Gallery Cosmos, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2015).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2015-05-15 |title=Gallery Cosmos goes for new art centre in city |url=https://www.observerbd.com/2015/05/15/88818.php |url-status= |work=The Daily Observer|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Manobotar Pokkhe Sahingsotar Biruddhe Chitrakarma'', Gallery Cosmos, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2015).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2015-02-20 |title=Fundraising exhibition at Gallery Chitrak |url=https://www.observerbd.com/2015/02/20/73624.php |work=The Daily Observer|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''11th Anniversary Exhibition by Galleri Kaya'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2015).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2015-06-05 |title=Galleri Kaya steps into 12 years with flying colours: An exhibition marking founding anniversary begins today |url=https://www.observerbd.com/2015/06/05/92420.php |work=The Daily Observer|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Brave Heart'', Gallery Cosmos, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2015).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2015-08-14 |title=Gallery Cosmos inaugurates group exhibition today |url=https://www.observerbd.com/2015/08/14/104867.php |work=The Daily Observer|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''13th Anniversary Exhibition by Galleri Kaya'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2017).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-05-05 |title=Galleri Kaya turns 13 |url=https://www.observerbd.com/details.php?id=71966 |work=The Daily Observer|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Jolokabbo'', Edge Gallery, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2017).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-12-01 |title=Musings in Watercolour at Edge Gallery in Gulshan-2 |url=https://www.observerbd.com/details.php?id=108818 |work=The Daily Observer|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* ''Contemporary and Modern Art of Bangladesh'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2017).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-12-02 |title=Exhibition of established artists open today |url=https://www.observerbd.com/details.php?id=108966 |work=The Daily Observer|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* ''Fourth National Sculpture Exhibition'', [[Bangladesh Shilpakala Academy]], Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2018).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-05-10 |title=National Sculpture Exhibition inaugurated |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/exhibition/national-sculpture-exhibition-inaugurated-1573918 |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* ''14th Anniversary Exhibition by Galleri Kaya'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2018).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-08-02 |title=Galleri Kaya celebrates 14th founding anniversary |url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/47504/galleri-kaya-celebrates-14th-founding-anniv |work=New Age|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* ''Still Life 2018'', Gallery Chitrak, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2018).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-10-26 |title=Group art exhibition opens today at Gallery Chitrak |url=https://www.observerbd.com/details.php?id=165134 |work=The Daily Observer|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* ''Soaked in Paper'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2019).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2019-03-02 |title=\u2019Soaked in Paper\u2019 underway at Galleri Kaya |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/exhibition/news/soaked-paper-under-way-galleri-kaya-1709203 |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* ''Festival of Fine Art'', Zainul Gallery, [[Faculty of Fine Arts, University of Dhaka]], Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2019).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2019-03-28 |title=\u2019Charukala Utshob 2019\u2019 starts in Gazipur |url=https://www.observerbd.com/details.php?id=190528 |work=The Daily Observer|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* ''15th Anniversary Exhibition by Galleri Kaya'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2019).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2019-07-04 |title=Exclusive group exhibition marking Galleri Kaya\u2019s 15th anniversary  |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/exhibition/news/exclusive-group-exhibition-marking-galleri-kayas-15th-anniversary-1766200 |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* ''Prologue 01'', Dhaka Gallery, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2019).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2019-07-14 |title=Dhaka Gallery sets sail showcasing 26 contemporary artists  |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/news/dhaka-gallery-sets-sail-showcasing-26-contemporary-artists-1770949 |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* ''Group Watercolour Exhibition'',  Zainul Gallery, [[Faculty of Fine Arts, University of Dhaka]], Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2020).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2020-02-09 |title=Watercolour Reigns Supreme |url=https://www.observerbd.com/details.php?id=243304 |work=The Daily Observer|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* [[Ekushey Padak]] (2006)\n* Prime Minister's Award for contribution in the beautification of Dhaka city  (2006)\n* Best Award in the Sculpture Exhibition by [[Bangladesh Shilpakala Academy]] (1976)\n* Best Award in the Life Oriented Art Exhibition, Dhaka Bangladesh Shilpakala Academy (1976)\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nShantir Paira sculpture at TSC DU (3).jpg|The sculpture \" Shantir Paira\" (means Dove of Peace ) infront of TSC of Dhaka University made by Sculptor Hamiduzzaman Khan. (Photo of November 2018)\nSculpture Life & The Lifeless 2019.jpg|Sculpture \"Life and the Lifeless\"\nLongest Mural in Bangladesh 2019.jpg| Mural \"Srom O Sristi\"\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Hamiduzzaman}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Dhaka Faculty of Fine Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi sculptors]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Ekushey Padak]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2017}}\n{{infobox person\n|name = Hamiduzzaman Khan \n|native_name=\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09bf\u09a6\u09c1\u099c\u09cd\u099c\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09a8 \u0996\u09be\u09a8\n|native_name_lang=bn\n|image=Hamiduzzam Khan.png\n|birth_date = {{birth year and age|1946}}\n|nationality=Bangladeshi\n|occupation=Sculptor\n|awards=[[#Awards|full list]]\n|birth_place = [[Kishoreganj]], [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]]\n|alma_mater = [[University of Dhaka]] <br/> [[Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda]] \n}}\n\n'''Hamiduzzaman Khan''' (born {{circa|1946}}) is a Bangladeshi sculptor.<ref name=dhakaart>{{cite web|url=http://dhakaartcenter.org/artist_directory/Hamiduzzaman_Khan.html|title=Hamiduzzaman Khan|publisher=Dhaka Art Center|accessdate=June 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKhan was born in 1946 in [[Kishoreganj District]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/exhibition/hamiduzzaman-khan-retrospective-opens-bnm-1482982|title=Hamiduzzaman Khan Retrospective opens at BNM|date=2017-10-29|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref> In 1962 he completed [[matriculation]] and got admitted into the erstwhile East Pakistan College of Arts and Crafts (now [[Faculty of Fine Arts, University of Dhaka]]). At the College of Arts and Crafts, he studied under the guidance of artists [[Zainul Abedin]], [[Safiuddin Ahmed]], [[Aminul Islam (artist)|Aminul Islam]], [[Mustafa Manwar]]. He earned [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] in 1967, graduating in painting. Khan was awarded an Indian government scholarship in 1973 to study for a [[Master of Fine Arts]] degree. He then went on to study at the [[University of Baroda Faculty of Fine Arts|Faculty of Fine Arts, Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda]], earning his master's degree in 1976.<ref name=dhakaart/> At Baroda, he studied in the tutelage of artists Raghav Kaneria, Mahendra Pandia, [[K. G. Subramanyan]]. <ref name=StarMag>{{Cite news |date=2010-10-10 |title=Symbolising Freedom |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/magazine/2010/12/02/art.htm |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nWhile a student at the College of Arts and Crafts, Khan experienced a road accident that fractured his skull, causing him to have a [[reconstructive surgery]] in the head. As there was no facility for the surgery in Dhaka, he was advised to receive treatment from the [[Royal Infirmary of Edinburgh]] in Scotland. On his way to Scotland by ship, Khan was impressed by seeing traditional African carvings in [[Dakar]] at a stopover. Following the surgery, he visited the [[British Museum]], [[Victoria and Albert Museum]], [[National Gallery]], [[Tate Galleries]].<ref name=MasterStroke/>{{Cite news |date=2008-03-19 |title=Master Stroke |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-28335 |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> In British Museum, Khan studied [[mummies]], statues from Greek, Egyptian and Roman times. Khan was particularly fascinated by sculptures in public places and the impact sculptures had in civic life. He was impressed by [[Henry Moore]]'s sculptures. In Italy, he experienced sculptures by [[Michelangelo]] at [[St. Peter's Basilica]] and in Paris, he saw artworks at the [[Louvre]]. Sculptures by [[Alberto Giacometti]] in Paris and [[Laoco\u00f6n and His Sons]] have had a lasting impact in his mind.<ref name=MasterStroke/> The experiences in Europe inspired Khan to study and focus his efforts on sculpture.<ref name=StarMag/><ref name=Jamini>{{Cite news |date=2013-10-13 |title=An Interview with Hamiduzzaman Khan |url=https://issuu.com/bengal-foundation/docs/jamini/8 |work=Jamini|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nDuring his stay in [[Baroda]] as a student, Khan made sculpture based on the [[Bangladesh War of Liberation]] and presented it to viewers in his first exhibit. The sculpture was a massacred human figure in lying position. Khan was praised by artist [[M. F. Husain]] and he was awarded first prize for the work in the exhibition celebrating twenty-five years of Faculty of Fine Arts, University of Baroda.\n\n==Career==\nKhan participated in his first national sculpture exhibition in 1976, and was awarded the first prize for his sculpture \"Dorja\"(door). He was appointed to make a bronze sculpture in Bangabhaban in 1981, entitled \"Bird Family\".\n\nIn the 1980s Khan was commissioned to decorate the [[Bangabhaban]] fountain with sculptural work.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2012-06-10 |title=Hamiduzzaman Khan's Solo Exhibition at Galleri Kaya: Watercolours and Sculptures Exposition |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2682859231.html |url-status=dead |work=Dhaka Courier |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414135727/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2682859231.html |archive-date=2016-04-14}}</ref> He created a bronze sculpture in Bangabhaban in 1981, entitled \"Bird Family\". In 1982, Khan's sculpture exhibition about the War of Independence was held at the Faculty of Fine Arts.  His sculpture \"Steps\" was installed in 1988 in the Olympic Park in Seoul, South Korea.<ref name=way>[http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMD6KG_The_Steps_5066851221_Olympic_Park__Seoul_Korea \"The Steps (\uc5ec\uc815) - Olympic Park  -  Seoul, Korea - Abstract Public Sculptures on Waymarking.com\"].</ref> In 1990, he placed a figurative sculpture, based on a fighter at the War of Liberation with one leg and arm amputed and a riffle on the other hand, the \"Samsaptak\" in the arena of Jahangirnagar University.\n\nKhan has created many paintings and sculptures while travelling abroad, including India, Korea<ref name=way /> and the United States. In 2015, he continued to exhibit his work and to conduct workshops.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://daily-sun.com/magazine/details/55568/JOLERDHARA|title=Jolerdhara|last=Sun|first=The Daily|work=Daily Sun|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n===Solo===\n* ''An Indigenous Minimalist'', Bengal Gallery of Fine Art, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2002).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2002-10-16 |title=An Indigenous Minimalist |url=https://bengalfoundation.org/reviews_archive/an-indigenous-minimalist/ |url-status= |work=Bengal Foundation |access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=bf>{{cite web|url=https://bengalfoundation.org/featured_artist/hamiduzzaman-khan/|title=Hamiduzzaman Khan|publisher=Bengal Foundation|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Homage to Matter'', [[British Council Bangladesh|The British Council]], Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2006).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2006-12-09 |title=Homage to Matter: A Garden by Hamiduzzaman Khan |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/2006/12/09/d612091401105.htm |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Recent Sculpture and Other Works'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2006).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2006-02-19 |title=\u2019Recent Sculpture and Other Works\u2019 |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/2006/02/19/d60219140199.htm |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''The Intimate World of Colour'', Gallery of Fine Art, [[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]], Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2008).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2008-08-24 |title=The Hamiduzzaman experience |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-51541 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Nocturnal Shades'', Bengal Gallery of Fine Arts, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2010).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2010-05-10 |title=Nocturnal Shades |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/magazine/2010/05/02/art.htm |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Time and Beyond'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2010).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2010-12-04 |title=Solo exhibition of Hamiduzzaman begins today |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-164698 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Watercolours & Sculptures'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2012).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2012-05-23 |title=Hamiduzzaman Khan\u2019s solo exhibition to open at Galleri Kaya |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-235257 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Earthly Treasures'', Athena Gallery, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2014).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2014-03-09 |title=Highlighting botanical and human forms |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/highlighting-botanical-and-human-forms-14657 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Stones'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2014).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2014-11-07 |title=Hamiduzzaman\u2019s exhibition till Nov 12 |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-in-brief-49158 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Stones-2'', Galleri Kaya, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2016).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2016-03-05 |title=Hamiduzzaman opens solo exhibit on 70th birthday |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/hamiduzzaman-opens-solo-exhibit-70th-birthday-786628 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Of Watercolours, Boats and Faces'', Shilpangan Gallery, Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2016).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2016-09-26 |title=Hamiduzzaman\u2019s art show begins Sept 30 |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/61513 |url-status= |work=The Independent|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Jiban Annashane'', [[Institute of Architects Bangladesh]], Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2017).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-01-09 |title=Many shades of life under spotlight |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/exhibition/many-shades-life-under-spotlight-1342303 |url-status= |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* ''Hamiduzzaman Khan Retrospective'', Nalinikanta Bhattashali Gallery, [[Bangladesh National Museum]], Dhaka, Bangladesh, (2017).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-10-28 |title=Hamiduzzaman Khan retrospective underway |url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/27148/hamiduzzaman-khan-retrospective-underway |url-status= |work=[[New Age (Bangladesh)|New Age]]|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-10-28 |title=Inauguration of Hamiduzzaman Khan's retrospective at BNM |url=https://www.bnm.gov.bd/bnmtoday/2017/10/30/inauguration-of-hamiduzzaman-khans-retrospective-at-bnm/ |work=[[Bangladesh National Museum]]|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n* ''Nocurnal Shades'', Abi